# TypeScript & Error Handling

## Errors

```typescript
// BAD — swallow or throw raw Error
try {
  await db.insert(...)
} catch (e) {}

// GOOD — typed domain errors
import { NotFoundError, ConflictError, BusinessRuleError } from "../../errors/AppError";

if (!product) throw new NotFoundError("Product not found");
if (stock < qty) throw new BusinessRuleError("Insufficient stock");
```

- Validate **all** inputs with Zod in ``*.schema.ts`` and wire ``validate(...)`` on routes — see ``zod-validation`` rule. Never trust raw ``req.body`` in services.
- Never return 500 for expected business failures.
- Use `logger.error({ err }, message)` for unexpected failures; let `globalErrorHandler` map the rest.

## Structure & readability

- Keep the 4-file module layout: `*.schema.ts`, `*.service.ts`, `*.controller.ts`, `*.routes.ts`, `*.test.ts`.
- Services: no Express types. Controllers: no business logic.
- Prefer clear names over abbreviations; group related helpers near their callers.
- After edits, ensure `pnpm build` (`tsc`) passes for touched code.
